review: My old ram had 1 of the 4 fail. So I upgraded from the the 32gb set to these 128gb and they work great.  Installed with intel 10900k and Asus rog z490 mb. Surprisingly I notice the biggest difference when browsing photos on my hard drives. The thumbnails and previews used to need buffer time and now it's near instant as I scroll. Second difference is apps load faster. I normally sit at 12-17gb utilization. Opened every app on my pc (adobe suite including Lightroom all of ms office topaz neo dxo steam VR tos and trading view plus 10 websites) and was "only" using about 47gb while rendering a video. Obviously I'd never have everything open all at once like that in normal use but was just curious what it would take to use up 132gb.  My pc did not slow down. Granted the gpu (2080s) can only keep up so much with all that. The render time would suffer bc the VR had priority over the video. Second gpu though and it would be unstoppable. That is next on the upgrade list now just to test playing VR while rendering videos.

The Corsair Vengeance RGB Pro 16GB 3200MHz sticks of ram were something I was looking into buying to upgrade my PC's ram as I wanted something speedy and aesthetically pleasing.  Since I have an older 2016 era PC I didn't have a motherboard compatible with DDR5 ram so this DDR4 set was the next best step.  Upon researching which ram sticks would have the best looking RGB lights I decided on these as I saw videos comparing different brands and I can confirm that these look pretty in my case.  The Corsair iCUE software is simple to use and offers a variety of different lighting packages that you can customize to your liking with several different patterns.  Compared to my old 8 gb ADATA sticks I have noticed an increase in overall speed when multitasking.  Overall I am satisfied with my purchase as after being skeptical with which ram sticks I should purchase buying these made me happy with how my PC looked and performed.  I plan to buy a new set whenever I decide to get a new PC.

Review - CORSAIR VENGEANCE RGB RS 64GB (2x32GB) DDR4 3600 (PC4-28800) C18 Memory-This memory is acceptable but as memory that portrays itself as the best money can buy I expected better.-DISAPPOINTMENTSWhen AMD DOCP (xmp) is turned off Corsair Vengeance RGB RS ram runs only at 2133 mts not the 2880 advertised right in the product name.-Configuring the RGB software for an Asus motherboard combining the Corsair iCue application with the Asus Armoury Crate application is a truly painful experience. Corsair doesn't provide any assistance either. Only after many web searches and finding discussions on some 3rd party tech forums was I able to figure out the RGB setup process. The iCUE software must be installed first and the RGB must be set in the iCue software before being recognized by the Asus Armoury Crate RGB software.-When using Asus Armoury Crate RGB software alone the Corsair RAM is not recognized. I've used other brands of the RGB ram that are recognized without additional software such as GSKILL and ADATA XPG.-When using 2 packages of 64GB to achieve 128GB my Asus ROG Strix X570-E mobo and Windows took 4 tries before it stabilized. On first boot Windows went BSOD before ever getting to the login screen. Only after turning off DOCP then getting into Windows then rebooting and turning then on DOCP in the uefi BIOS and then booting again did the memory finally train and synchronize correctly.-OTHER THOUGHTSUnless purchasing a pre-tested package of 4 RAM sticks it seems to be pure chance to be able to get 4 sticks of RAM from 2 different packages of 2 sticks to run together regardless of brand or price.-CONCLUSIONSBe forewarned that if you think buying expensive "fancy ram" will avoid setup and configuration problems think again. Even with expensive Corsair fancy ram expect to work at to get the RAM to function optimally.

The last item I had with several blinking lights on it was my toy robot ... when I was 4 years old. The RGB LED craze to put flashing lights on every computer component for the most part seems absolutely asinine. I only purchased this particular model because I needed two 32GB sticks and I have used Corsair Vengeance in the past with good results. I mounted them properly and they work just fine in my Gigabyte Aorus Master Z390 motherboard. By default the LEDs are set to a slow "breath" cycle that changes to another hue every 5 seconds or so. If you want to take full control of the LEDs you need to use Corsair's monster bloatware program iCUE that will likely #### up more things than it fixes. I went into iBloat and set the LEDs to map to the dimms temperature sensor so I could tell if they got too warm. Once I made this adjustment the voltage regulator on my Corsair HX1200i PSU started clicking. Two days later and I am still troubleshooting the LEDs (the HX1200i has been rock solid for more than 2 years). If the LEDs are set to off the clicking disappears. I am still fooling with finding a compromise. Stay tuned ....

I needed to upgrade the RAM in my workstation (MSI TRX40 Pro Wifi motherboard AMD 3970X CPU Nvidia 3090 GPU OS = Linux Mint 20.1 64-bit Xfce). I did not really want RGB LEDs but during the installation I found this feature to be helpful because when the machine was booted I could instantly see which of the DIMMS were illuminated. In fact I needed to re-seat the RAM a few times to get all of the DIMMs to register. At first the machine set the frequency to 2133 MHz but after going into the UEFI BIOS and manually setting the frequency to 3200 MHz DRAM voltage to 1.35 volts and timings to 16-18-18-36 I was able to run the RAM at its rated speed. Installation was relatively easy and considering current prices this RAM was a fairly good value for the money.

Corsair has always been my favorite company for gaming memory and storage. Unfortunately I will not be buying from them again. This gaming memory chip has been working well for about a year.  Then it starting to fail and caused "blue screens". After confirming with memtest that the "blue screens" are indeed memory related I reached out to Corsair support to replace the memory since there is limited lifetime warranty.  Unfortunately they have been slow to respond.  After multiple days support responded and requested info on serial numbers and receipt which were promptly provided.  Now it has been 8 days since I heard from support after repeatedly requesting for an update while my machine is "blue screening" everyday.  I sent one last email to support this morning and if I don't receive a response from them I will never buy from Corsair in my personal and professional life.  It may not be a big deal to Corsair but if this review sways someone away from buying this or other Corsair products due to support then this review has served its purpose.  Thanks for reading my frustration and disappointment with Corsair.

There is not much I can say for the memory itself it's well built and crushes the competition. As for the software that is a different story. I have an ASUS current motherboard and the Corsair iCue software requires that I have ASUS Aura installed so it can control Aura RGB lighting. Well if you want everything to work well together then you better have all RGB hardware baring the Corsair name. If you don't then good luck my friend because you are in for annoyances and difficult to find solutions. First noticeable annoyance is a hardware disconnect sound every time the iCue software starts. Secondly you will not want iCue to control Asus Aura devices if you have other name brand products in your system (Like a Coolermaster AIO cooler). Other name brand RGB product's lighting can freeze up especially if they use a 5V addressable headers on the motherboard. In the end I could not get rid of the Disconnect sound but I was able to disconnect iCue software from controlling ASUS Aura devices by deleting the ASUS plugin from the Corsair Plugins folder. If they fix their software and give clear easy instructions that are easily accessible and easy to read then I will gladly give a 5 star rating.

I purchased 4x8Gb 3200 thinking they would run 3200 out of the box but they do not.  You have to overclock them like using the XMP1 to get 3200 out of them and then my system will sometimes not boot.  So it is not very stable at the advertised 3200 speed.  CPU-Z says it is DDR-2132 memory even though I bought 3200 memory.  I don't know if this is normal or not but I do have to run either XMP1 or XMP2 to get the 3200 speed I can also just over clock the memory to 3200 to get the advertised speed but you will not get it out of the box and in my case running it at 3200 makes it unstable on boot.  I have not had any problems after boot running it at 3200 but it will not always boot.I am going to try and replace it with the 3600 and see if that helps.However I must say the memory itself is beautiful with the RGB lighting and that is why I am trying the 3600 and returning the 3200 because I absolutely love the looks of the memory.  I just wish I had know it has to be overclocked to get the advertised speed.  Maybe I just don't know how 3200 memory works but it should tell you in description that you must over clock to get the advertised speeds.

What can I say?  I have unable to reach the advertised 3600 no matter what setting I do with the Bios.  It says it can make the 3600 speed according to XMP but it lies.  It only reaches 3200 at best and that is not even true when I run CPU-Z where it clearly shows its only running at 1066 Mhz.I am using the ROG STRIX Z370F Gaming MoBo and I updated the bios thinking that was the problem.I will have a better idea if this works and will update my rate when my new MoBo Vid Card and other things make it here.  Then I will try that same RAM in the new build and see if it can reach advertised speed.

I ordered 2 kits of 16gb 3200. First set would not run at 3200 at all. Pulled one kit out of PC and tested the kits individually. Would boot at 3200 but would not open any games without them crashing almost immediately. Sent those kits back and had Amazon send me two new ones. These kits lasted together for about 30 minutes with no issues at XMP settings.  Stress tested on prime95 large ffts( or whichever one tested the RAM) and it went for 15 minutes with no errors. Then played Star Wars BF2 for another 15 minutes perfectly fine. Then out of nowhere blue screen Computer rebooted and as soon as I signed in blue screen rebooted again and as soon as login screen loaded blue screen again.  Then windows went into recovery mode. So I pulled out the ram and put my older corsair vengeance kit in that runs at 3600MHZ and no issues I also have another vengeance kit in another computer at 3200 that is the same specs as these white rgb ones and it runs perfect at XMP. Both kits also run perfectly fine together in the same computer at 3200mhz CL16 so I know my motherboard and cpu can handle 4 sticks 32GB total at 3200mhz no problem. So I do not know what corsair is doing to pass these kits off as "3200mhz" but clearly they are no longer capable of actually running at those speeds with whatever batch I ended up getting. Shows that corsair doesn't actually test the ram for long enough. Sending these ones back for a refund and ordering a g skill kit to try that out.

I bought this locally at Bestbuy because I was pretty sure it was going to have to be returned. The package says it is designed for both the intel and AMD platform. When using it with the ROG Maximus XIII Hero (WiFi 6E) Z590 it fails after 3066MHz. At 3200 system will post but will cause corruption on the file system. Testing the RAM at this speed caused lots of errors when testing it. +3200MHz to 3600MHz including using XMPII settings causes the system to not post with a 5d error. This might work well on with other systems but the ROG Maximus XIII Hero (WiFi 6E) Z590 is a failed combo.I might test this RAM in a few other systems before it goes back and will report my findings in an update if I do. I didn't buy this here but thought I would warn others that have the same board to stay away if they are wanting to hit the rated MHz. I love the look of the RAM by default system boots with rainbow effects until the system is booted and the Armoury Crate software is loaded. There is a plugin from the manufacturer to allow the RGB to work with Asus' Armoury Crate software. I will say Corsair's RGB software is a tad bit better out the gate than the Armoury Crate. Corsair's prebuilt lighting effects are better. I am not looking at setting my whole desk up with their RGB lighting kits for your desk. The movie mode looks epic and I am looking to add that to my home theatre room. If you haven't looked at it you're missing out on what RGB can really do and Corsair has outdone themselves in my opinion.As for RAM for my system I may have to choose another brand as it looks like the only stable RAM they offer is 2666MHz from what I can tell. This RAM is not bad at 3066MHz but you're not going to hit the support for 3200MHz for this board speeds over 3200MHz are considered the overclock range.

Thought I would grab a set of these 16 GB 3200 (8x2) DIMMs to include in my new build Ryzen 5 3600 ASRock X570m Pro4  Sapphire 5700XT Nitro in a Corsair 280X case.  All went as planned until I ran into what appears to be a common issue with these DIMMs defaulting to 2133 Mhz. XMP listed it a 16 16 16 34 setting however would not boot After multiple unsuccessful trips down manual CAS and voltage setting trying to reach anything higher than 2133 I took one last shot and looked for a updated BIOS.  Low and behold ASRock went from BIOS 1.9 to 2.30 ( Released 12/9/19)  after a quick DL a reboot into the flash utility and my fingers were crossed the update was successful.  The DIMMs still showed as a default 2133 Mhz but I loaded the XMP values and away with the boot it went!  SUCCESS!  Morale to the story update the bios before you head back to the store for an RMA.

We have never had problems with any of the Vengeance or Dominator DDR4 and have decided to hold off on buying DDR5. I personally do not game thus the Z690 boards with DDR4 should suffice. We're cutting back on computer building to about 12 per year for family and church support. We've built a few gaming units for others but we will stop. My husband is almost 75 and he just needs to do it for a part-time hobby. He's purchased one Z690 for DDR5 and one for DDR4.with the political games being played I think it may be time to stop altogether. We've settled on specific hardware that has consistently worked (i.e. Aoris by Gigabyte corsair Cougar  Nvidia Samsung) and over the last 20+ years since we built 386 units we've only had one board fail purchased from Amazon or Newegg. We have trusted Corsair for their excellence and Amazon for their consistence in shipping timely and with a few exceptions have purchased mainly from Amazon. We just don't want to get involved in keeping up with the newest trend anymore and it's probably time to quit! Hope to convince the old guy he can stop working. He tells me he wants to find a job. Anyway Corsair is the way to go if you want to be sure.

I ordered this product as part of my personal new pc build. I assembled everything correctly and everything was working fine. After 3 months of usage I had several issues and blue screens on my pc as well as window update issues. After a thoroughly research and testing my hardware for issues I discovered that there was an issue with my computer's memory. My motherboard was Working as a dual channel memory so I tried starting my pc using on one of the memory modules and then the other one. Using that I discovered that my pc couldn't boot with one of them and I finally found the issue. I contacted Amazon support and informed them about the issue. Since this product was under Amazon they send me a replacement pair in new condition. Trying those modules made my day. Everything was working as it should be. Overall despite my little adventure I am giving 5 stars for customer support.

So I've been building myself a great gaming PC. Out of the lot the biggest issue I've experienced is the memory. I learned the hard way. Other than looking very slick the memory just won't boot at 3200mhz if you've mixed another kit with it. Isn't it just me but I remember doing this back in the days without any issues. With today's RAM it looks completely different and any mixing makes you lose any optimization you've paid for getting a 3200mhz RAM.Long story short I did a lot of back and forth with Corsair support when experiencing this problem. They essentially told me I shouldn't mix kits even if they are all of the same model number (2 kits of 2x8GB CMW16GX4M2C3200C16W). I read a lot about this after and it seems pretty deep. Sometimes it works sometimes it doesn't... The consumer ends up troubleshooting their way out of it. To me it makes no sense to me that I cannot mix 2 of the same exact kits but it just doesn't work any way I tried it. If I just kept 2x8GB (essentially 1 kit) then it works at 3200mhz. If I want to use 2 kits it is stuck at its lowest speed. I've purchased a lot of Corsair gear with that new PC but I'm overall disappointed that Corsair doesn't stand much behind their product in the case of mixing RAM. I was able to do it with a less familiar brand (XPG). Pretty disappointing to say the less. Now I'm stuck using only 2x8GB and I'll return the second kit. I learned the hard way by wasting a lot of time energy and obviously the deal I got was on the second kit no chances of keeping the deal.Pros:- Look slick! Love the RGB!- Will reach 3200mhz if you use only 1 kit on your motherboard.Cons:- Cannot mix with anything even another kit of the same model/timing/etc. You cannot *ever* upgrade your memory after that. You're done forever unless you feel like paying for complete new RAM sticks and throw those away.- Corsair support is slow at times and I felt like I was stuck with my own issue. The tech support guy wasn't of much help and I had to prove that it just wouldn't work. Luckily I'm tech savvy so I was ale to troubleshoot it myself. End result won't work any way you put it. Thanks Corsair!

I already have similar frequency RAM kit from corsair with 16 18 18 36 config. This is addition to the kit to increase the RAM size. So installing this set in addition was a task as I had to manually set the timings in BIOS which is slower than my earlier kit. First I thgt system will automatically adapt to slower settings but it did not happen and Instarted getting blue screen errors. Upon looking into BIOS I figured out that timings are still running with older RAM settings. Turning off XMP and setting voltage values to recommended values and then the timings stopped the error. Happily running the system with 64gigs of ram now.

This review is for the Corsair Vengeance RGB RT 16GB (2x8GB) DDR4 3600MHz C18 Desktop Memory Kit of 2. If you are not an IT savvy Ram is where data is stored before any processing occurs within your computer‚Ä¶ so it‚Äôs one of the most important hardware in your computer after the CPU and the GPU. DDR4 is the latest dynamic RAM technology mostly only compatible with newer motherboards. The benefit of using DDR4 instead of DDR3 is that DDR4 RAM has higher overall speed increased transfer rates and less voltage which means less overall power consumption by 40% and boosts performance and bandwidth by 50% to DDR3 RAM.Corsair it‚Äôs always been a trusted brand for me I have used their RAMs in my gaming PC‚Äôs I‚Äôve built in the past decades.Would highly recommend upgrading your computer with this DDR4 Corsair Vengeance Memory if you‚Äôre regularly using programs that require a lot of memory like games engineering programs or photo and video editing software. I‚Äôve got the 2 x 8 GB module with 3600MHz which is fine for gaming and for everyday use. Also it worth to check your motherboard before you buy it as it might not be compatible or will not allow to RAM to run on the highest MHz‚Äôs. To find your motherboard model in Windows 10 go to the Power User Task Menu type in ‚Äúrun‚Äù and then ‚ÄúMSinfo32.‚Äù. This Ram is mainly optimised for AMD 300/400 and 500 series motherboardsInstalling the rams is simple and easy it‚Äôs a plug and play hardware that does not require any software. I would suggest saving anything what you‚Äôve been working on the computer as most of this information is kept on the ram until you save it and you will lose it when you turn off the computer. Remove your old ram and put in your new RAM sticks match the notches with the gaps in the motherboard and push firmly and evenly until you hear a ‚Äòclick‚Äô. After you‚Äôve installed the new RAM kit close your computer. Restart everything and reboot then you RAM is ready to use by your CPU.The RGB lighting effects can easily be changed using Corsair‚Äôs own software to match several pre-sets including one snapped to the temperature of the memory so it can go slowly change from green to yellow orange etc depending on how warm they get. This is particularly handy to keep an eye on the current temperature levels inside your case. Use the CORSAIR iCUE software or your motherboard manufacturer‚Äôs software to create your own setting. This RGB colour features makes this Corsair Vengeance a beast ram a perfect hardware for gamers. In the amazon description is not mentioned however on the packaging box it says comes with a Limited Lifetime Warranty.Compare to other DDR4 RAM on the market this one is a little bit pricier but it‚Äôs a CORSAIR. It‚Äôs a well trusted brand with great reputation.  My computer very stable with this ram boot time significantly less than before all programs run instantly all my heavy RAM consuming apps like Adobe software VirtualBox works great with less crashing and no freeze. I'm very impressed and highly recommend it.

The media could not be loaded.                                                                                ¬†Great RAM sticks. Really complement my now ageing PC build. When i first ordered the parts for my PC back in 2016 i knew i wanted a white and black colour scheme so got a case to and motherboard (the asus Z170-A) Took 3 years for me to get white RAM sticks but i am glad i waited.Install as with most RAM was an absolute breeze. Popped the old sticks out and slotted the new sticks in and ''voila''! Boot up in to BIOS and set the speed to 3200mhz as advertised. Everything is running sweet.The RGB lighting is amazing if you are in to that sort of thing like i am. I have recently become addicted to anything RGB so have got a razer RGB mouse Razer RGB Keyboard Razer RGB desk mat Razer RGB Headphone stand... blah blah you get the idea. I also recently bought and installed the Corsair Hydro 100i Platinum RGB CPU cooler which like these RAM sticks are excellent.The software to control the lighting effects is called Corsair icue. I found the software to be very user friendly after coming from Razer Synapse. As soon as it was installed it instantly detected both my RAM and CPU cooler and i can sync the lighting patterns for the Corsair kit nicely.My bedroom now looks like an acid rave when i am playing games and me and my cat love it.There is cheaper RAM available which is just as good at being RAM as these are however i would say that if you like RGB and have the spare cash then do get these. Just please check online and in forums to ensure that your motherboard is compatible.
